#2
ggplot(data = SAT, aes(salary, sat)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
  ggtitle("Average SAT scores by average teacher salary") + xlab("Average Teacher Salary") +
  ylab("Average SAT Score")

"Just because there is a trend or correlation in the data where as average teacher salary increases, average SAT score decreases, this does not imply causation. There could be underlying conditions in the data or perhaps this data is not repersentative of the entire population."

#4
?cut
my_labels <- c("low", "medium", "high")
div <- cut(SAT$frac, breaks = c(0,22,49,Inf), labels = my_labels)
#5
ggplot(data = SAT, aes(salary, sat)) + geom_point(aes(color = factor(div, labels = c("Low (<=22%)",   
      "Medium(23-49%)", "High (>=50%)")))) + geom_smooth(method = lm, se = F) +
      ggtitle("Average SAT scores by average teacher salary") + xlab("Average Teacher Salary") +
      ylab("Average SAT Score") + labs(color = "% of students taking SAT")

ggplot(data = SAT, aes(salary, sat, color = factor(div, labels = c("Low (<=22%)", "Medium(23-49%)", 
      "High (>=50%)")))) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, fullrange = T) +     
      ggtitle("Average SAT scores by average teacher salary") + xlab("Average Teacher Salary") +
      ylab("Average SAT Score") + labs(color = "% of students taking SAT")

#7
#sum(SAT$frac > 50)
GT50 <- subset(SAT, frac >= 50)
ggplot(GT50, aes(salary, sat)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = lm, se = F) + 
  ggtitle("States with >=50% take SAT") + xlab("Average Teacher Salary") + ylab("Average SAT Score")

#8
model <- lm(sat ~ salary, data = GT50)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = sat ~ salary, data = GT50)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -37.787 -13.646  -3.735  11.258  53.127 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 837.5714    38.8653  21.551 3.02e-13 ***
## salary        1.4603     0.9989   1.462    0.163    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 24.07 on 16 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1178, Adjusted R-squared:  0.06269 
## F-statistic: 2.137 on 1 and 16 DF,  p-value: 0.1631
"For every $1 increase in average teacher salary, we expect to see an increase of 1.46 points in average SAT score for students in states in which at least 50% of students take te SAT. For a $0 increase in average teacher salary, we predict the average SAT score for students in states where more than 50% of students take the SAT to be about 837. At the 5% significance level, we do not have enough evidence to conclude that every $1 increase in average teacher salary significantly increases SAT score for students in states where 50% or more students take the SAT since our p-value, .163, is greater than alpha = .05"
## [1] "For every $1 increase in average teacher salary, we expect to see an increase of 1.46 points in average SAT score for students in states in which at least 50% of students take te SAT. For a $0 increase in average teacher salary, we predict the average SAT score for students in states where more than 50% of students take the SAT to be about 837. At the 5% significance level, we do not have enough evidence to conclude that every $1 increase in average teacher salary significantly increases SAT score for students in states where 50% or more students take the SAT since our p-value, .163, is greater than alpha = .05"
#9
plot(rstandard(model) ~ fitted(model),
     main="Standardized residuals by fitted values",
     ylab="Standardized residual",
     xlab="Fitted value")
abline(h=0)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

hist(rstandard(model),xlab="Standardized Residuals",main="")

qqnorm(rstandard(model))
qqline(rstandard(model))

"Yes, the regression assumptions do appear to have been met. For the fitted values vs standardized residuals plot, there does not appear to be a fan shape or any clear trends in the plot, so we can assume there is independence between the residuals and that there is constant variance. For linearity, the Normal Q-Q plot shows that most the data with the exception to the top 2 points is along the best fit line. Lastly, the histogram reveals that data does follow a Normal Distribution, therefore we can assume normality. However, because the sample size is only 18 observations, we would need more data to be certain the linear regression conditions have been met."
## [1] "Yes, the regression assumptions do appear to have been met. For the fitted values vs standardized residuals plot, there does not appear to be a fan shape or any clear trends in the plot, so we can assume there is independence between the residuals and that there is constant variance. For linearity, the Normal Q-Q plot shows that most the data with the exception to the top 2 points is along the best fit line. Lastly, the histogram reveals that data does follow a Normal Distribution, therefore we can assume normality. However, because the sample size is only 18 observations, we would need more data to be certain the linear regression conditions have been met."
